:"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"},{"type":"tags","id":"13227"},{"type":"tags","id":"13635"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/17887/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/17887/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"53276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"53279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"54899"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/17887/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/17887/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-year-old child presents with a skin and soft tissue infection. Culture grows \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E that is resistant to flucloxacillin. Testing reveals the presence of the mecA gene.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how the mecA gene confers antibiotic resistance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Production of \u03b2-lactamase enzyme","Efflux pump removal of antibiotic","Altered penicillin-binding protein with low \u03b2-lactam affinity","Reduced porin expression preventing drug entry"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mecA gene is responsible for methicillin resistance in \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA). This gene encodes PBP2a (penicillin-binding protein 2a), which has a significantly lower affinity for \u03b2-lactam antibiotics compared to normal penicillin-binding proteins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of \u03b2-lactamase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is a different resistance mechanism found in some strains of \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E. \u03b2-lactamase hydrolyses the \u03b2-lactam ring of penicillins, but this is not the mechanism associated with the mecA gene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEfflux pump removal of antibiotic\u003C/strong\u003E is a resistance mechanism used by some bacteria to actively pump antibiotics out of the cell, but this is not how mecA confers resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAltered penicillin-binding protein with low \u03b2-lactam affinity\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct mechanism. PBP2a encoded by mecA can continue to catalyse cell wall synthesis even when other penicillin-binding proteins are inhibited by \u03b2-lactam antibiotics, allowing the bacteria to survive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced porin expression preventing drug entry\u003C/strong\u003E is a resistance mechanism more commonly seen in Gram-negative bacteria where antibiotics must pass through porins in the outer membrane. This is not relevant to \u003Cem\u003ES. aureus\u003C/em\u003E, which is Gram-positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRSA infections are particularly important in paediatric populations as they can cause severe skin and soft tissue infections, as well as more invasive diseases. Understanding the mechanism of resistance helps explain why alternative antibiotics such as vancomycin or clindamycin are needed for MRSA infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The mecA gene encodes PBP2a, an altered penicillin-binding protein with low affinity for \u03b2-lactam antibiotics.","Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) maintains cell wall synthesis even in the presence of \u03b2-lactam antibiotics due to PBP2a."],"references":["Peacock SJ, Paterson GK. Mechanisms of methicillin resistance in Staphylococcus aureus. Annual Review of Biochemistry. 2015;84:577-601."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101825"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"25060"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120090/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101825"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-14T14:29:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-14T14:31:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"17887"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101825/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101825/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120090"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101825/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101825/relationships/content"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/group","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9/relationships/group"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagH